<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05152l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05152l">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05152l"> 152(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Trist&apos;s elder bro dies / He is &hellip; named Fumier</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">We know how Herodotus (II. 132, 171) refuses to mention the name of Osiris. The true and great name of Allah is a secret name, and similarly with the gods of Brahmanism and the real name of Confucius. Orthodox Jews apparently avoid the name Jahweh altogether. We may compare &lsquo;Thank Goodness&rsquo;, &lsquo;Morbleu&rsquo;&mdash;and the majority of euphemisms. <mark>Among the Hindus if one child has been lost, it is customary to call the next by some opprobrious name. A male child is called <i>Kuriya</i>, or Dunghill</mark>&mdash;the spirit of course knows folk as their names and will overlook the worthless. <small> C.K. Ogden and I.A. Richards <a name="OMOM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OMOM"><cite title="source">The Meaning of Meaning</cite></a> (London: Kegan Paul, 1923) 37-8</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: French <i>fumier</i>: dunghill. </mm> </dd></dl>
